Had a chatty Lyft driver. After learning I do research on cancer:

👵🏻: You know what causes cancer?

👩🏻‍💼: Yea?

👵🏻: Sugar!

👩🏻‍💼: Wow, that's very impressive! Ppl usually don't think of that.

👵🏻: Yep! We have a prophet in our church wrote a whole book about this.

full_text: @ExOncTc 5/6 We found that a more positive feeling after exercise was associated with higher confidence in and more positive expectations from exercising the next day, which in turn was associated with a higher exercise level. #ExOncTC #cancersurvivorship https://t.co/EQuwThOVVN
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 5/6 We found that a more positive feeling after exercise was associated with higher confidence in and more positive expectations from exercising the next day, which in turn was associated with a higher exercise level. #ExOncTC #cancersurvivorship https://t.co/EQuwThOVVN'

full_text: @ExOncTc 4/6 Participants reported exercising 16 days across the 42 monitoring days, with an average of 18 minutes of exercise each day. We did not find a direct association between feelings after exercise and exercise level the next day. #ExOncTC https://t.co/cvwrVCpeft
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 4/6 Participants reported exercising 16 days across the 42 monitoring days, with an average of 18 minutes of exercise each day. We did not find a direct association between feelings after exercise and exercise level the next day. #ExOncTC https://t.co/cvwrVCpeft'

full_text: @ExOncTc 3/6 We had 97 #cancersuvivors in this study. They completed brief surveys via a PDA 📱 each morning about their exercise confidence and expectations, and before/after each exercise session about their feelings over a total of 42 days across a 6-month intervention period. #ExOncTC https://t.co/pGEE1QTkBb
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 3/6 We had 97 #cancersuvivors in this study. They completed brief surveys via a PDA \xf0\x9f\x93\xb1 each morning about their exercise confidence and expectations, and before/after each exercise session about their feelings over a total of 42 days across a 6-month intervention period. #ExOncTC https://t.co/pGEE1QTkBb'

full_text: @ExOncTc 2/6 Using data from an exercise intervention for #endometrialcancer survivors, we tested if feelings after exercise would impact participants’ confidence in and expectations from exercising the next morning, which in turn would affect their activity level for that day. #ExOncTC https://t.co/9ujQmKwDjo
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 2/6 Using data from an exercise intervention for #endometrialcancer survivors, we tested if feelings after exercise would impact participants\xe2\x80\x99 confidence in and expectations from exercising the next morning, which in turn would affect their activity level for that day. #ExOncTC https://t.co/9ujQmKwDjo'

full_text: @ExOncTc 1/6 Studies have shown that how you feel after exercising (e.g., happy 😊, tired 😪, sore 😩, relaxed 😇) could influence your decision to exercise the next time. Yet little is known about the mechanism underlying such effects. #ExOncTC https://t.co/ipJwD1ODzk

full_text: @ExOncTc 6/6 The preliminary results suggest that daily glucose patterns based on CGM data could be used as modifiable indicators of obesity-related cancer risk. Future diet and physical interventions could aim to improve daily glucose patterns as a cancer prevention strategy. #ExOncTC 👏 https://t.co/tFXq7Ee968
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 6/6 The preliminary results suggest that daily glucose patterns based on CGM data could be used as modifiable indicators of obesity-related cancer risk. full_text: @wired4story @ExOncTc The biomarkers we analyzed include HbA1c, IGF-1, IGF-2, and IGFBP-2 levels.
full_text(utf-8): b'@wired4story @ExOncTc The biomarkers we analyzed include HbA1c, IGF-1, IGF-2, and IGFBP-2 levels.'

full_text: @ExOncTc 5/6 The study sample had HbA1c level of 5.6, MAGE of 2.2, and 3 hyperglycemic events. HbA1c was marginally associated with # of hyperglycemic events and with IGF-1. MAGE was positively associated with IGF-2. Hyperglycemic events was marginally associated with IGF-2. #ExOncTC https://t.co/nwu1Q9d3Uq
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 5/6 The study sample had HbA1c level of 5.6, MAGE of 2.2, and 3 hyperglycemic events. HbA1c was marginally associated with # of hyperglycemic events and with IGF-1. MAGE was positively associated with IGF-2. Hyperglycemic events was marginally associated with IGF-2. #ExOncTC https://t.co/nwu1Q9d3Uq'

full_text: @ExOncTc 4/6 Glycosylated hemoglobin (HbA1c), IGF-1, IGF-2, and IGFBP-2 levels were obtained by blood draw. 📈 Linear regression models were used to examine the association between glucose measures and the biomarkers. #ExOncTC https://t.co/vM4LvExCPN
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 4/6 Glycosylated hemoglobin (HbA1c), IGF-1, IGF-2, and IGFBP-2 levels were obtained by blood draw. \xf0\x9f\x93\x88 Linear regression models were used to examine the association between glucose measures and the biomarkers. #ExOncTC https://t.co/vM4LvExCPN'

full_text: @ExOncTc 3/6 Participants completed a 7-day monitoring period using the Dexcom G4 PLATINUM continuous glucose monitor (CGM). Hyperglycemic events (glucose>140 mg/dL) and mean amplitude of glycemic excursions (MAGE), which indicates daily glucose variability, was calculated. #ExOncTC https://t.co/Z2IWFcU5Qe
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 3/6 Participants completed a 7-day monitoring period using the Dexcom G4 PLATINUM continuous glucose monitor (CGM). Hyperglycemic events (glucose>140 mg/dL) and mean amplitude of glycemic excursions (MAGE), which indicates daily glucose variability, was calculated. #ExOncTC https://t.co/Z2IWFcU5Qe'

full_text: @ExOncTc 2/6 Less is known about if daily glucose patterns might be associated with cancer risk biomarkers. This study aimed to quantify daily glucose patterns and explore their relationships with cancer-related biomarkers, in a sample of nondiabetic overweight and obese adults. #ExOncTC https://t.co/hmr3yS0sdi
full_text(utf-8): b'@ExOncTc 2/6 Less is known about if daily glucose patterns might be associated with cancer risk biomarkers.
